    <section>
        <h2>Lists and List Methods</h2>
        <p>
        Lists are one of Python's most versatile data structures. They're mutable, ordered sequences 
        that can contain elements of different types.
        </p>
    
        <pre><code>
            # Creating and modifying lists
            numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

            # Adding elements
            numbers.append(6)        # Add to end
            numbers.insert(0, 0)     # Insert at position
            numbers.extend([7, 8])   # Add multiple elements

            # Removing elements
            numbers.pop()            # Remove last
            numbers.remove(0)        # Remove specific value

            # List operations
            print(len(numbers))      # Length
            print(numbers[0])        # First element
            print(numbers[-1])       # Last element
            print(numbers[1:4])      # Slicing

            # List methods
            numbers.sort()           # Sort in place
            numbers.reverse()        # Reverse in place
            print(numbers.count(3))  # Count occurrences

            # List comprehension
            evens = [x for x in numbers if x % 2 == 0]
            print(evens)
        </code></pre>
  </section>

  <section>
        <h2>Dictionaries</h2>
        <p>
        Dictionaries store key-value pairs and are extremely useful for organizing related data. 
        They're mutable and unordered (in Python 3.6+, they maintain insertion order).
        </p>
    
        <pre><code>
            # Creating dictionaries
            student = {
                "name": "Bob",
                "age": 20,
                "grade": "A"
            }

            # Accessing values
            print(student["name"])
            print(student.get("age"))

            # Adding/updating values
            student["major"] = "Computer Science"
            student["age"] = 21

            # Dictionary methods
            print(student.keys())    # All keys
            print(student.values())  # All values
            print(student.items())   # All key-value pairs

            # Iterating over dictionary
            for key, value in student.items():
                print(f"{key}: {value}")

            # Dictionary comprehension
            squares = {x: x**2 for x in range(5)}
            print(squares)
        </code></pre>
  </section>

